<details>
<summary><h3 style="display:inline-block">Notes</h3></summary>
<p>Some roots don't follow derivation rules exactly, because of how their sounds interact, such as t-b-n.</p>
<p><i>ng</i> is a sound that is preferred before another consonant rather than after, and it will never appear at the start of a word. Additionally, if a pattern would place <i>ng</i> directly after some sounds like <i>k</i> or <i>g</i>, then <i>ng</i> will switch places with the following vowel. For example, the tool noun of <i>k-s-ng</i> is not <i>kusngo</i> but <i>kusong</i>. However, the elative form <i>kosngei</i> does not change.</p>
  <p>When it comes to derivation templates, a <b>C</b> represents a single consonant from the root. An <b>X</b> represents a consonant from the root that is doubled in the word (s-t-k + CaXXoCu = sattoku).</p>
  <details>
  <summary><h4 style="display:inline-block">Soft, Hard and Double Final trilats</h4></summary>
  <p>(This whole thing is covered again later under the Prefixed Derivations header, but I'm also sticking it here.)</p>
    
<p>Trilaterals like to do fun things based on the consonants involved in them, which can change how they derivate in certain scenarios (like with prefixed verbal nouns).</p>
<p>Soft roots are trilaterals that begin with "soft" consonants, including <i>h, l, m, n, ng, s, w,</i> and <i>y</i>.</p>
<p><b>h-n-t</b> hunting<br>
<b>s-n-b</b> snow<br>
<b>y-k-n</b> forgetting, the unknown<br>
<b>s-m-h</b> permission<br>
<b>w-n-h</b> gentleness, caressing</p>

<p>Hard roots are trilaterals that begin with "hard" consonants, including <i>b, d, k, p,</i> and <i>t</i>.</p>
<p><b>k-m-y</b> smallness<br>
<b>k-w-y</b> strength, power<br>
<b>t-n-d</b> standing</p>

<p>Conditional consonants include <i>ch, j,</i> and <i>sh</i>, which are considered hard before <i>l</i> and other conditional consonants, but soft before anything else.</p>
<p><i>Hard</i><br>
<b>j-l-m</b> flight<br>
<b>j-sh-l</b> readiness, preparation</p>

<p><i>Soft</i><br>
<b>j-p-h</b> carrying, pregnancy</p>

<p>Some other rules:</p>
<p>If the middle radical is an <i>h</i>, then the root is treated as a double final, regardless if the root is hard or soft.</p>
<p>If the first two consonants of a root are the same, then that root is considered soft regardless of whether the consonants themselves are hard, soft, or neutral.</p>
<p>Double final roots are triconsonantal roots that have the same consonant for the second and third radicals, and have slightly different derivation patterns in some cases.</p>
<p>If a root would fulfill multiple criteria, then the applicable category that is lowest on this list is used. For example, a soft double final root would derivate as a double final.</p>
</details>
<details><summary><h4 style="display:inline-block">Irregular Roots</h4></summary>

<p>A while ago there was a subset of roots called open roots, that were sort of like trilaterals except the first radical didn't exist, and was denoted with a <b>'</b>. Most open roots that used to exist fell out of use or merged with their bilateral counterparts, but there are some that still exist like <b>'-ng-s</b> (which you can see in this generator).</p>

<p>Since open roots are defunct and nonproductive, all nouns derived from them are considered broken. Because there are (two) irregular roots in this generator, I've included a table of their derivations, but new words are not made with this schema.</p>

