<details><summary><h4 style="display:inline-block">The List</h4></summary>
<p>When prefixing with <b>pa-</b>, <b>(ch)o-</b>, and <b>ki-</b>:<br>
The unilateral takes the form <b>-Ca</b>.<br>
The bilateral takes the form <b>-CaC</b>.<br>
The trilateral soft takes the form <b>-CCaC</b>.<br>
The trilateral hard and double radical take the form <b>-CaCCa</b>.</p>

<p>When prefixing with <b>(h)i-</b>, <b>mo-</b>, <b>bu-</b>, and <b>lu-</b>:<br>
The unilateral takes the form <b>-Co</b>.<br>
The bilateral takes the form <b>-CoC</b>.<br>
The trilateral soft takes the form <b>-CCoC</b>.<br>
The trilateral hard and double radical take the form <b>-CoCCa</b>.</p>

<p>When prefixing with <b>hei-</b> and <b>yo-</b>:<br>
The unilateral takes the form <b>-Ci</b>.<br>
The bilateral takes the form <b>-CiC</b>.<br>
The trilateral soft takes the form <b>-CCiC</b>.<br>
The trilateral hard and double radical take the form <b>-CiCCa</b>.</p>

  <p>When prefixing with <b>aXX</b>:<br>
The unilateral <b>cannot be prefixed</b> in this way.<br>
The bilateral takes the form <b>aXXaC</b>.<br>
The trilateral soft, hard and double radical take the form <b>aXXaCCa</b>.</p>
  
</details>
</details>

<details><summary><h3 style="display:inline-block">Other Changes</h3></summary>
  <p>Any <b>unilateral</b> derivation that starts with an <b>a</b> has the initial <b>a</b> removed before the prefix is placed, and like usual <i>pa</i> becomes <i>pae-</i> when attached directly. Also, you can't form a prefixed unilateral superlative.</p>

<p>One derivation that changes form is the passive participle, from <b>eiCi</b> to <b>-Cei</b>.</p>
<p><b>i + eiki</b> > <b>ikei</b><br>
<b>ki + eini</b> > <b>kinei</b><br>
<b>mo + eimi</b> > <b>momei</b></p>

<p>Also, because the unilateral augmentative is just the habitual reduplicated, both halves take the prefix.</p>
<p><b>asu'asu</b> mass death; an epidemic<br>
<b>isu'isu</b> a mass killing; genocide</p>

<p><b>Bilaterals</b> remain largely unchanged, taking prefixes without a fuss except for the bilateral habitual, which doesn't take prefixes.</p>

<p><b>Trilaterals</b> have a few more changes.</p>
<p>Soft trilateral active participles change from <b>CaCiCae</b> to <b>-CCiCae</b>.</p>
<p><b>chamigae</b> that which covers / hiding, especially in shadow<br>
<b>pachmigae</b> that which is hidden / being hidden in shadow</p>

<p>However, double final and hard roots take the same form as the verbal noun, replacing the final <b>a</b> with <b>ae</b>. This means that the middle vowel matches that of the prefixed verbal noun.</p>
<p><b>bannae</b> that which watches<br>
<b>kibannae</b> that which watches one another<br>
<b>mobonnae</b> that which anticipates<br><br>
<b>jattae</b> that which connects<br>
<b>heihittae</b> that which connects to the self<br><br>
<b>bawimae</b> that which is sad or mourns<br>
<b>ibowmae</b> that which saddens<br>
<b>kibawmae</b> that which mourns together<br>
<b>mobowmae</b> that which mourns</p>

<p>This also includes roots that have <i>h</i> as a middle radical, regardless of whether the root is hard or soft.</p>
<p><b>dahigae</b> that which descends<br>
<b>idohgae</b> that which drags down<br><br>
<b>mahijae</b> that which 1. seizes 2. possesses<br>
<b>pamahjae</b> that which is possessed</p>

<p>The active participle of the intensive form always takes the same shape as the hard root, while maintaining the aXX.</p>
<p><b>kahigae</b> that which continues<br>
<b>akkahgae</b> that which continues forever</p>

<p>Also, the trilateral habitual participle changes from <b>CoCuC</b> to <b>-CCuC</b>.</p>
<p><b>jomuy</b> most convincing<br>
<b>pajmuy</b> being convinced the most</p>
</details>
</details>

